        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-03-28T19:07:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-03-28T19:07:00-05:00" n="16"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d16">
                <head>16. Circular Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss>
                    to <gloss type="to">Certain Diplomatic Missions</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d16fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 440.002/2–2858. Confidential. Drafted by Myerson; cleared in <gloss
                            target="#t_EURBNA1">EUR/BNA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_EURRA1"
                            >EUR/RA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_EURWE1">EUR/WE</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_E1">E</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_OT1">OT</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_E1">E</gloss>/TAD, and <gloss target="#t_W1">W</gloss>; and
                        signed for <persName>Dulles</persName> by <persName corresp="#p_TBELIII1"
                            >Timmons</persName>. Sent to Bern, Bonn, Brussels, Copenhagen, The
                        Hague, London, Luxembourg, Oslo, Rome, Paris, Stockholm, and Vienna and
                        pouched to Ankara, Athens, Dublin, Lisbon, Ottawa, and Reykjavik.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-03-28T19:07:00">March 28, 1958, 7:07
                            p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>911. A. <gloss target="#t_CA1">CA</gloss>-8151.<note n="1" xml:id="d16fn1">
                        <ref target="#d12">Document 12</ref>.</note> B. <gloss target="#t_POLTO1"
                        >Polto</gloss> 3020 rptd or pouched other addressees;<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d16fn2">
                        <ref target="#d15">Document 15</ref>.</note> The Hague’s 1864,<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d16fn3">In telegram 1864 from The Hague, March 27, the Embassy
                        reported that the approach on <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> had been
                        made to Dutch Foreign Office officials, who had expressed the view that U.S.
                        intervention, if undertaken, should be directed toward the Germans, and
                        specifically toward <persName corresp="#p_AK1">Adenauer</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BH1">Von Brentano</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_HW1">Hallstein</persName>. (Department of State, Central
                        Files, 440.002/3–2758)</note> London’s 5650,<note n="4" xml:id="d16fn4">
                        <ref target="#d14">Document 14</ref>.</note> Brussels 1316<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d16fn5">In telegram 1316 from Brussels, March 27, the Embassy
                        reported on the approach made to the Belgian Government with regard to the
                            <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. (Department of State, Central
                        Files, 440.002/3–2758)</note> and Copenhagen’s 728.<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d16fn6">In telegram 728 from Copenhagen, March 27, the Embassy
                        reported that it had made the requested approach to the Danish Foreign
                        Office, which had expressed its belief that the United States was really not
                        enthusiastic about <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. (<hi rend="italic"
                            >ibid</hi>.)</note> Luxembourg for <persName corresp="#p_BWW1"
                        >Butterworth</persName> and Embassy. Paris for <gloss target="#t_USRO1"
                        >USRO</gloss> and Embassy.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In carrying out instruction <gloss target="#t_REF1">ref</gloss> A (or if
                        necessary in follow-up contacts) addressee Missions should take care dispel
                        firmly any lingering doubts re US attitude warm support <gloss
                            target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss> negotiations. This connection Dept wishes
                        make clear that addressees authorized their discretion draw on entire
                        section I <gloss target="#t_REF1">ref</gloss> A in informal contacts.
                        (Naturally presentation should be adapted omit reference “US strategic
                        objectives” para I E, reference to effect on sterling, or any other points
                        obviously inappropriate for such use.)</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Re timing problem should leave no doubt US favors fastest possible
                        progress consistent overriding objective achieving final agreement on
                        arrangements which in line principles summarized <gloss target="#t_REF1"
                            >ref</gloss> A (and other messages same series) and which can be
                        defended before US public opinion and in <gloss target="#t_GATT1"
                            >GATT</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>. Continue believe
                        necessary guard against premature pressures which could for example result
                        in early agreement at excessive cost in terms undesirable commercial policy
                        features <gloss target="#t_FTA1">FTA</gloss>. End <gloss target="#t_FYI1"
                            >FYI</gloss>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
